  <h2 id="tools">The Four Treasures of the Study</h2>

  <p>Traditional calligraphy requires the 文房四宝 (wénfáng sì bǎo) — the Four Treasures of the Study. These four tools have been the foundation of Chinese writing and painting for over two thousand years, and each one plays a specific role in the creative process:</p>

  <table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 20px 0;">
    <thead>
      <tr style="background: #dc2626; color: white;">
        <th style="padding: 12px; text-align: left;">Treasure</th>
        <th style="padding: 12px; text-align: left;">Chinese</th>
        <th style="padding: 12px; text-align: left;">Description</th>
        <th style="padding: 12px; text-align: left;">Beginner Tip</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-weight: 600;">Brush (笔)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">毛笔 (máobǐ)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Made from animal hair — wolf, goat, or mixed</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Start with a medium wolf-hair brush for Regular Script</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc; border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-weight: 600;">Ink (墨)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">墨 (mò)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Ink stick ground on inkstone with water, or bottled ink</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Bottled ink is fine for practice — saves time</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-weight: 600;">Paper (纸)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">宣纸 (xuānzhǐ)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Absorbent rice paper (Xuan paper)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Practice on newspaper or grid paper first</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc; border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-weight: 600;">Inkstone (砚)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">砚台 (yàntái)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Stone slab for grinding ink stick with water</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Not needed if using bottled ink</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>The brush (毛笔 máobǐ) is the most important of the four treasures. Brushes are categorized by their hair type: wolf hair (狼毫 lángháo) produces firm, sharp strokes ideal for Regular Script; goat hair (羊毫 yángháo) is softer and more absorbent, favored for expressive Running and Cursive styles; and mixed hair (兼毫 jiānháo) blends both qualities and works well for beginners. The size of the brush matters too — a medium brush with a tip about one centimeter in diameter is the most versatile starting point.</p>

  <p>Ink (墨 mò) comes in two forms: ink sticks and bottled liquid ink. Traditional ink sticks are made from pine soot or oil soot mixed with animal glue, then pressed into decorative molds. Grinding the ink stick in small circles on a wet inkstone is itself a meditative ritual that helps the calligrapher settle into focused concentration before writing. The grinding process lets you control the ink density — more grinding produces thicker, darker ink. Bottled ink is perfectly acceptable for practice sessions, but many experienced calligraphers prefer the subtle tonal variations that freshly ground ink provides.</p>

  <p>Xuan paper (宣纸 xuānzhǐ) is the traditional paper of choice because its absorbent fibers interact beautifully with ink, allowing for subtle variations in tone and texture. Raw Xuan paper (生宣 shēng xuān) is highly absorbent and favored for expressive styles, while treated Xuan paper (熟宣 shú xuān) has a sizing agent that slows ink absorption, making it more forgiving for beginners. For your earliest practice sessions, newspaper or inexpensive practice paper with printed grid lines is an economical choice that lets you focus on stroke mechanics without worrying about wasting expensive materials.</p>

  <p>The inkstone (砚台 yàntái) serves as both grinding surface and ink reservoir. Fine-grained stones from Guangdong (端砚 Duān yàn) and Anhui (歙砚 Shè yàn) are the most prized, but any smooth-surfaced inkstone will work for beginners. If you use bottled ink, a small ceramic dish can serve the same purpose as an inkstone for holding and diluting your ink.</p>

  <h2 id="five-styles">The Five Major Styles</h2>

  <p>Chinese calligraphy has evolved through five major scripts, each with distinct characteristics:</p>

  <table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 20px 0;">
    <thead>
      <tr style="background: #dc2626; color: white;">
        <th style="padding: 12px; text-align: left;">Style</th>
        <th style="padding: 12px; text-align: left;">Chinese</th>
        <th style="padding: 12px; text-align: left;">Era</th>
        <th style="padding: 12px; text-align: left;">Characteristics</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-weight: 600;">Seal Script</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">篆书 (zhuànshū)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">~2000 BC</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Oldest style, round and symmetrical, used on official seals</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc; border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-weight: 600;">Clerical Script</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">隶书 (lìshū)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">~200 BC</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Wider, flatter strokes with distinctive "wave" endings</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-weight: 600;">Regular Script ⭐</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">楷书 (kǎishū)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">~200 AD</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Standard style used today — clear, structured, best for beginners</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc; border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-weight: 600;">Running Script</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">行书 (xíngshū)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">~200 AD</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Semi-cursive, strokes may connect, faster to write</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-weight: 600;">Cursive Script</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">草书 (cǎoshū)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">~200 AD</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Highly simplified, abstract, often illegible to non-experts</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>Understanding the historical progression of these five styles gives you valuable context for your own practice. Seal Script, the most ancient form, was standardized by the first emperor Qin Shi Huang as part of his effort to unify Chinese writing. Its rounded, symmetrical forms are still used today on official seals and name chops, giving this ancient script a living connection to modern life. Clerical Script emerged as government clerks needed a faster writing method, flattening the round forms of Seal Script into wider, more horizontal characters with distinctive wave-like endings on certain strokes.</p>

  <p>Regular Script, developed during the late Han and Wei-Jin periods, became the standard for printed text and formal writing. It is the style taught in schools throughout China today and the foundation that all calligraphy students should master first. Its clear structure and consistent proportions make it the ideal script for developing proper technique. Running Script evolved as a natural acceleration of Regular Script, where some strokes connect and simplify while the overall structure remains recognizable. Most everyday handwriting in Chinese naturally tends toward Running Script. Cursive Script takes simplification to its extreme — strokes merge, characters compress, and the result is a highly expressive but often illegible art form that prioritizes energy and rhythm over readability.</p>

  <p>Each style is associated with legendary calligraphers whose works remain the gold standard for study. Wang Xizhi (王羲之, 303-361 AD), often called the Sage of Calligraphy, is celebrated for his masterful Running Script, particularly his famous Preerta of Orchid Pavilion (兰亭序 Lántíng Xù). Yan Zhenqing (颜真卿, 709-785 AD) developed a bold, powerful Regular Script style known for its thick, muscular strokes, and his work is often the first model that beginners copy. Liu Gongquan (柳公权, 778-865 AD) created a contrasting Regular Script style with sharp, angular precision. Zhao Mengfu (赵孟頫, 1254-1322 AD) of the Yuan Dynasty brought elegance and fluidity to Regular Script, and his style remains widely studied. For beginners, copying the works of Yan Zhenqing or Liu Gongquan is the most common starting approach, as their clear, well-defined strokes are easier to analyze and replicate.</p>

  <h2 id="basic-strokes">The Eight Basic Strokes (永字八法)</h2>

  <p>The character 永 (yǒng, eternal) contains all eight fundamental strokes of Chinese calligraphy. This is why it has been the starting point for calligraphy students for over 1,500 years:</p>

  <table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 20px 0;">
    <thead>
      <tr style="background: #dc2626; color: white;">
        <th style="padding: 12px; text-align: center;">#</th>
        <th style="padding: 12px; text-align: left;">Stroke Name</th>
        <th style="padding: 12px; text-align: left;">Chinese</th>
        <th style="padding: 12px; text-align: left;">Direction</th>
        <th style="padding: 12px; text-align: left;">Key Technique</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
