        <td style="padding: 10px; font-weight: 600;">Horizontal</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">横 (héng)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Left to right</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Slightly upward angle, press at start and end</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; text-align: center; font-weight: 600;">3</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-weight: 600;">Vertical</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">竖 (shù)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Top to bottom</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Straight and strong, like a pillar</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc; border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; text-align: center; font-weight: 600;">4</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-weight: 600;">Hook</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">钩 (gōu)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Sharp turn at end</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Pause, then flick in the hook direction</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; text-align: center; font-weight: 600;">5</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-weight: 600;">Left-falling</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">撇 (piě)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Upper right to lower left</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Start thick, taper to thin — like a knife</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc; border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; text-align: center; font-weight: 600;">6</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-weight: 600;">Right-falling</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">捺 (nà)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Upper left to lower right</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Start thin, press heavier, then lift at the end</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; text-align: center; font-weight: 600;">7</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-weight: 600;">Rising</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">提 (tí)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Lower left to upper right</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Quick upward flick — light and energetic</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc; border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; text-align: center; font-weight: 600;">8</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-weight: 600;">Turning</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">折 (zhé)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Direction change</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Pause at the corner, then change direction cleanly</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>When practicing each stroke, pay close attention to three phases: the entry (起笔 qǐ bǐ), the body (行笔 xíng bǐ), and the exit (收笔 shōu bǐ). The entry is where you place the brush tip on the paper and establish the stroke's initial shape. In Regular Script, most entries use a technique called "hidden tip" (藏锋 cáng fēng), where the brush first moves slightly opposite to the stroke direction before reversing into the main movement. This creates clean, rounded beginnings rather than sharp, exposed points. The body of the stroke requires steady, controlled movement at a consistent speed. The exit is where you either lift the brush cleanly, pause and reverse slightly, or flick to create a hook or taper. Mastering these three phases for each of the eight basic strokes gives you the building blocks for writing any Chinese character.</p>

  <p>A practical approach to stroke practice is to dedicate focused sessions to individual strokes before combining them into characters. Write a single horizontal stroke fifty times, paying attention to consistent thickness, angle, and length. Then do the same with vertical strokes. Only when you feel comfortable with individual strokes should you attempt full characters. This isolated stroke practice may feel tedious, but it builds the muscle memory and brush control that will make your character writing much stronger in the long run.</p>

  <h2 id="techniques">Essential Techniques</h2>

  <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(280px, 1fr)); gap: 16px; margin: 24px 0;">
    <div style="background: #eff6ff; border-radius: 12px; padding: 20px;">
      <p style="margin: 0 0 8px; font-weight: 700; color: #1e40af;">✋ Brush Grip</p>
      <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95em;">Hold the brush vertically with three fingers (thumb, index, middle) near the upper-middle of the handle. Keep your wrist elevated — do not rest it on the paper. Your entire arm should move, not just your fingers.</p>
    </div>
    <div style="background: #f0fdf4; border-radius: 12px; padding: 20px;">
      <p style="margin: 0 0 8px; font-weight: 700; color: #166534;">🪶 Pressure Control</p>
      <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95em;">Press harder for thick strokes, lighter for thin ones. Each stroke begins with a "hidden tip" entry — press down then pull to start cleanly. This creates the characteristic "bone structure" of good calligraphy.</p>
    </div>
    <div style="background: #fef3c7; border-radius: 12px; padding: 20px;">
      <p style="margin: 0 0 8px; font-weight: 700; color: #92400e;">🧍 Posture</p>
      <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95em;">Sit upright with both feet flat on the floor. The paper should be directly in front of you. Your non-writing hand holds the paper steady. Breathe naturally and maintain relaxed shoulders.</p>
    </div>
    <div style="background: #fce7f3; border-radius: 12px; padding: 20px;">
      <p style="margin: 0 0 8px; font-weight: 700; color: #9d174d;">⚡ Speed</p>
      <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95em;">Beginners should write slowly and deliberately. Speed comes naturally with practice. Rushing produces messy strokes. Think of each stroke as having a beginning, journey, and ending.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>Beyond these core techniques, ink loading is a skill that beginners often overlook. Dip your brush fully into the ink, then gently press the tip against the side of the ink dish to remove excess and shape the bristles into a fine point. Too much ink causes blotchy, uncontrolled strokes, while too little ink produces dry, scratchy marks. The ideal ink load produces strokes that are rich and dark in the center with slightly lighter edges. As you gain experience, you will learn to use intentional ink variation — starting a character with a fully loaded brush and allowing the ink to gradually thin as you write creates a natural rhythm of dark and light called "dry brush" (枯笔 kū bǐ) effects, which advanced calligraphers use for expressive purposes.</p>

  <p>The concept of "structure" (结构 jiégòu) in calligraphy refers to how the individual strokes are arranged within the imaginary square that each character occupies. Good structure means balanced proportions, consistent spacing between strokes, and appropriate density distribution. Characters should feel centered and stable, neither leaning to one side nor appearing cramped or overly spread out. Using grid paper with cross-hairs helps beginners develop an eye for structure by providing visual reference points for stroke placement.</p>

