        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.2em;">水 木 火 土</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Complex combinations, hooks</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>The characters in the table above are chosen not only for their simplicity but also because they introduce you to fundamental structural concepts one at a time. Week one focuses purely on horizontal and vertical strokes, the two most basic movements. The characters 一, 二, and 三 teach you to space parallel horizontal strokes evenly, while 十 introduces the critical intersection of horizontal and vertical strokes. Week two adds diagonal strokes and the dot, with 人 and 大 teaching you to balance left-falling and right-falling strokes symmetrically. Week three introduces enclosed structures through characters like 口 (a simple box) and 日 (a divided box), which require precise turning strokes and proportional division of interior space. By week four, you are combining all stroke types in more complex characters like 水 and 火, which demand confident hook strokes and careful balance of multiple elements.</p>

  <p>As you move beyond these foundational characters, a powerful study method is to practice by copying classical copybooks (字帖 zìtiè). These are printed collections of exemplary characters by master calligraphers, and they serve as your primary teacher in the absence of a live instructor. Place the copybook next to your practice paper and carefully observe each stroke before attempting to reproduce it. Study the thickness variations, the angles, the spacing, and the overall proportions. Then write the character several times, comparing each attempt to the original. This process of careful observation followed by deliberate practice is how calligraphers have trained for centuries.</p>

  <h2 id="practice-routine">Daily Practice Routine</h2>

  <div style="background: #f0f9ff; border: 2px solid #0ea5e9; border-radius: 12px; padding: 24px; margin: 20px 0;">
    <p style="margin: 0 0 12px; font-weight: 700; font-size: 1.1em; color: #0369a1;">30-Minute Daily Practice</p>
    <p style="margin: 0 0 6px;"><strong>5 min:</strong> Warm up — draw circles, waves, and straight lines to loosen your arm</p>
    <p style="margin: 0 0 6px;"><strong>10 min:</strong> Stroke practice — choose 2-3 basic strokes and repeat each 20 times</p>
    <p style="margin: 0 0 6px;"><strong>10 min:</strong> Character practice — write today's target character 15-20 times</p>
    <p style="margin: 0;"><strong>5 min:</strong> Free practice — write a character you enjoy for relaxation</p>
  </div>

  <p>Consistency matters far more than session length. Thirty minutes of focused daily practice will produce better results than sporadic two-hour sessions on weekends. The physical motions of calligraphy are built through repetition over time, and your muscle memory develops most effectively with regular, spaced practice. Many practitioners find that calligraphy becomes the most enjoyable part of their day — a quiet half hour of focused attention that serves as a counterbalance to the constant digital stimulation of modern life.</p>

  <p>Modern calligraphy is experiencing a significant revival around the world. In China, calligraphy education has been reintroduced into school curricula, and calligraphy competitions attract thousands of participants. Outside of China, interest in Chinese calligraphy has grown alongside the broader popularity of mindfulness practices, as people discover that brush writing offers the same mental health benefits as meditation: reduced stress, improved focus, and a sense of creative accomplishment. Social media platforms have also played a role in this revival, with calligraphy videos attracting millions of viewers who are drawn to the mesmerizing rhythm of brush on paper. Whether you approach calligraphy as a cultural pursuit, a language learning tool, or a meditative practice, the skills you develop through regular brush work will deepen your appreciation for Chinese characters and connect you to one of humanity's longest continuous artistic traditions.</p>

